# Part 3: Reflection

## What issues were discovered during the review?
Several issues were identified during the review. The main concerns involved limited client-side validation, weak handling of edge cases such as empty dashboard states, and opportunities to reduce duplicated rendering logic in the front-end JavaScript. While the code was functional, some of these issues would affect the user experience and make future updates more difficult if left unresolved.

## Were any architectural inconsistencies identified?
No major architectural violations were found, but there were some minor concerns related to separation of concerns in the front-end code. In particular, some JavaScript sections combined API communication and DOM updates too closely. While this is manageable at the MVP stage, it could create maintainability problems as the application grows. Refactoring these responsibilities into clearer functions would better align the implementation with the intended architecture.

## What would have happened if this code were merged without review?
If the code had been merged without review, the application would still function, but several avoidable issues would remain. Users might encounter confusing error situations, future developers would have a harder time maintaining the code, and the front-end could become more difficult to extend cleanly in later sprints. Over time, these issues could slow development and increase the likelihood of defects.

## How will you integrate code reviews into future sprints?
In future sprints, code reviews should be built into the definition of done for all meaningful features. Before merging, each major feature should be reviewed against a checklist covering correctness, architecture, maintainability, security, and performance. Review comments should be documented directly in pull requests, and team members should address required changes before integration. This process will improve code quality, reduce regressions, and help the team maintain a more professional development workflow.
